imate that cattle-to-cattle transmission rates are non-linearly density dependent. The basic reproductive ratio for our conventional within-herd model, estimated for scenarios with no statutory controls, increases from 1.5 (0.26-4.9; 95% CI) in a herd of 30 cattle up to 4.9 (0.99-14.0) in a herd of 400. Under this model we estimate that 50% (33-67) of recurrent breakdowns in Britain can be attributed to infection missed by tuberculin testing. However this figure falls to 24% (11-42) of recurrent breakdowns under our alternative model. Under both models the estimated extrinsic force of infection increases with the burden of missed infection. Hence, improved herd-level testing is unlikely to reduce recurrence unless this extrinsic infectious pressure is simultaneously addressed.', 'original': None}", 'Authors': "[{'first_name': 'Andrew J. K.', 'last_name': 'Conlan', 'initials': None, 'researcher_id': 'ur.0753273207.43', 'grid_ids': array(['grid.5335.0'], dtype=object), 'orcid': array(['0000-0002-2593-6353'], dtype=object), 'corresponding': True, 'raw_affiliations': array(['Disease Dynamics Unit (DDU), Department of Veterinary Medicine, University of Cambridge, Cambridge, United Kingdom'],
