 not participate in the fidelity checks. Overall, teachers found the online resource facilitative of teaching health and wellbeing and several recommendations regarding the resource were provided to inform further evaluations. Recruitment and retention rates suggest that the teacher led intervention is feasible and acceptable to both teachers, parents and children. Initial findings provide promising evidence that given a greater sample size, a longer intervention exposure period and changes made to the resource, teachers' use of HSR could enhance measures of health and wellbeing in children.", 'original': None}', 'Authors': "[{'first_name': 'Duncan S.', 'last_name': 'Buchan', 'initials': None, 'researcher_id': 'ur.01035724706.07', 'grid_ids': array(['grid.15756.30'], dtype=object), 'orcid': array(['0000-0002-4320-4615'], dtype=object), 'corresponding': True, 'raw_affiliations': array(['School of Health and Life Sciences, University of the West of Scotland, South Lanarkshire, Scotland, United Kingdom'],
